The paper discusses the optimization of machine learning models, specifically deep nets, which are commonly used in computer vision (cs.CV) and natural language processing (cs.CL). The method of auxiliary coordinates (MAC) is a general approach to optimize nested functions, which is relevant to optimization (cs.DC) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also describes ParMAC, a distributed-computation model for MAC, which involves parallel computing (cs.DC) and distributed systems (cs.DS). Finally, the paper applies ParMAC to learn binary autoencoders for fast image retrieval, which is a specific application of computer vision (cs.CV) and neural networks (cs.NE).
